{{Infobox artist | name = Diango Hernández | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = Diango Hernández Torres | birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1970}} | birth_place = [[Sancti Spíritus, Cuba]] | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | death_place = | nationality = Cuban | spouse = Anne Pöhlmann | field = | training = | movement = | works = | patrons = | awards = | elected = | website = http://www.diangohernandez.com | bgcolour = }}
'''Diango Hernández''' is a [[Cuba]]n artist.
== Biography == Hernandez was born in 1970 in [[Sancti Spíritus, Cuba|Sancti Spíritus]], Cuba. He earned a degree in [[industrial design]] at the [[Havana Superior Institute of Design]] (ISDI). After graduation in 1994 he began a collaboration experience together with [[Ernesto Oroza]], Juan Bernal, [[Francis Acea]] and [[Manuel Piña]] under the name of Ordo Amoris Cabinet<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.diangohernandez.com/tag/ordo-amoris-cabinet-1994-2003/ |title=Ordo Amoris Cabinet (1994-2003)|website=diangohernandez.com|accessdate=21 August 2017}}</ref> after the [[Latin]] words for "order" and "love". From 1996 until 2003 Ordo Amoris Cabinet was only formed by Hernández and Francis Acea. The duo's sculptural installations were exhibited throughout [[Cuba]], [[Europe]], and [[North America]]. Hernández’s works has been included at the 51st [[Venice Biennale|Venice Art Biennale]] (Arsenale, 2005), [[São Paulo Art Biennial]] (2006), [[Biennale of Sydney]] (2006), [[Kunsthalle Basel]] (2006), Munich’s [[Haus der Kunst]] (2010), London’s [[Hayward Gallery]] (2010) and more recently with a survey at the [[Museum of Modern and Contemporary Art of Trento and Rovereto|MART]] in Rovereto, Italy, (2011). Hernández currently lives and works in [[Düsseldorf]], [[Germany]].
